{{Japanese temple|Name = Takisan-ji|Image = ]][[File:Takisan-ji Temple Hondou, Yamagomori Taki-cho Okazaki 2022.jpg|270px]]<br />Main Hall (Important Cultural Property)<br />(]][[2022]] January)|Location = {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|ja|愛知県}}{{ill|Okazaki|ja|岡崎市}}{{ill|Taki-cho|ja|滝町}} Yamagomori 107|Coordinates = {{Coord|34|59|17.37|N|137|12|20.26|E|region:JP-23_scale:20000_type:landmark|display=inline,title|name=滝山寺}}|Mountain Name = Kisshōdarani-zan|Temple Name = Yakujūō-in|Sect = {{ill|Tendai Sect|ja|天台宗}}|Main Image = {{ill|Yakushi Nyorai|ja|薬師如来}}|Founded = Traditionally during the era of Emperor Tenmu (673-686)|Founder = Traditionally {{ill|En no Gyōja|ja|役小角}}|Alternate Names = |Official Name = 吉祥陀羅尼山藥樹王院瀧山寺|Cultural Properties = Main Hall, Sanmon Gate, Wooden Standing Statue of Kannon Bosatsu, and Standing Statues of Brahma and Indra (Important Cultural Properties)|Map = {{Location map|Japan Aichi|lat_deg=34|lat_min=59|lat_sec=17.37|lon_deg=137|lon_min=12|lon_sec=20.26|label=Takisan-ji|mark=Japanese Map symbol (Temple).svg|marksize=11|position=center|width=200|float=center}}}}'''Takisan-ji''' (滝山寺) is a {{ill|Tendai Sect|ja|天台宗}} Buddhist temple located in {{ill|Okazaki|ja|岡崎市}}, {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|ja|愛知県}}. == Overview ===== History ===The mountain name is Kisshōdarani-zan, and the temple name is Yakujūō-in. The temple is renowned for the {{ill|Takisanji Oni Festival|ja|滝山寺鬼まつり}}.{{ill|Takisan Tōshō-gū|ja|滝山東照宮}} is located to the east, and the {{ill|Hiyoshi Sannōsha Main Hall|ja|滝山東照宮#日吉山王社本殿}} is to the north of the Main Hall.According to the "Takisan-ji Engi" (a historical record of the temple; existing manuscripts are from the early modern period), the temple was established during the {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代}} by order of Emperor Tenmu. {{ill|En no Gyōja|ja|役小角}}, a legendary ascetic, enshrined a golden statue of {{ill|Yakushi Nyorai|ja|薬師如来}} found in the {{ill|Aoki River|ja|青木川}}. The temple, initially named "Kisshō-ji," was later abandoned and fel